1 Introduction
Int this study I implemented a generic multilayer feedforward neural network. These are a popular type of
neural network that form a hierarchical learning framework by stacking layers of hidden units. These models
can be thought of as universal function approximators that have a tremendous capacity to learn complex
distributions over high dimensional datasets [1]. Neural nets typically require thousands to hundreds of
thousands of labeled training examples to learn complex data generating distributions. However, several
characteristics of neural networks make them well suited for augmentation with active learning strategies.
In particular, the majority of neural net classiﬁers are probablistic models which are trained to learn
p(y|x)
where
x
is a p-dimensional vector of features and
y
is a distribution over a set of class labels. The ultimate
goal of these discriminative models is to predict with high accuracy the label examples that it has not seen by
learning the data generating distribution from those examples were drawn. As such, neural network classiﬁers
are trained to minimize the "difference" between the known labels of a training set and the predictions it makes
on said set. More speciﬁcally, these classiﬁers are trained via maximimum likelihood, or equivalently by
minimizing the negative log likelihood of the networks predictions under the emperical data distribution. As
a result, the topmost layer of these models outputs a class conditional distribution over the data labels and
prediction performed by simply selecting the label with highest probability.
2 Algorithms
The probablistic nature of these models makes them well suited for active learning techniques such as
uncertainty sampling. This is a method by which the labels of training points are requested in a greedy approach.
The high level goal of these techniques is to maximize the amount of information that can be extracted from a
set of unlabeled points by requesting the labels of examples of which the model is most uncertain of at any given
point during the training process. In this study I implemented two standard pool-based uncertainty sampling
methods: a margin based approach in which uncertainty is quantiﬁed by ﬁnding the training point which has the
smallest difference between its top two class predictions, i.e.

3 Methods
To study the impact of active learning in the context of image classiﬁcation I implemented a multilayer
feedforward neural network in which labels of training points were selected via the two uncertainty sampling
methods described above as well as a random learner. Given a training set with 4119 examples, each with 26
features corresponding to 8 unique classes, training was performed with a ﬁxed budget of 2500 oracle calls as
follows: First, 250 calls were spent obtaining a small labeled pool in order to pretain the network. Measures
were taken to ensure that each of the 8 classes were equally represented. The model was pretrained with 5
passes over this set. Two pools of data were maintained throughout the training process, namely those whose
labels had been requested from the oracle and those whose labels were still unknown. During each iteration,
the label of one training example from the unlabeled pool was requested based on one of the three selection
strategies (BVSB, entropy, random). The class conditional probabilities obtained from the output of the
softmax layer were used for both active strategies to rank each example and expand the labeled pool. Each time
the labeled pool recieved a new training point the entire batch of labeled examples was used to update network
parameters via stochastic gradient descent (SGD). Updates were made to each trainable parameter via the
backpropagation algorithm, and loss was quantiﬁed via cross entropy. In order to prevent overﬁtting, L2 weight
decay was applied to the weights of each layer and hidden units randomly shut off via stochastic dropout. Next,
a grid search over hyperparameters such as number of hidden units per layer, choice of activation function
(sigmoid/relu/tanh), learning rate and dropout rate was performed. This led to the following architecture and
parameters:
30 ! 30 ! 8
, dropout rate of 0.5, learning rate of 0.001, sigmoid activation, and weight decay of
0.001. Each model was trained until the oracle budget was spent. 5 permutations were performed over each
model with different random initializations and performance metrics from each trial were averaged.

5 Discussion
There are several key takeaways from the results of this study. Firstly it appears that the entropy based
uncertainty sampling strategy outperformed both the BVSB and random learner. This is evidenced by the fact
that this model achieved higher accuracy overall accuracy on both datasets (roughly 93% easy, 85% medium).
In terms of f1-score (harmonic mean of precision and recall) it is again clear that the entropy selection method
is superior to BVSB and the random learner, ﬁgures 7 and 17. With respect to the class labels it appears that
plasma membrane was the most difﬁcult to classify whereas all models were able to correctly label actin
examples with near 100% accuracy. In summary, I have studied the affects of active learning methods paired
with deep learning neural networks and demonstrated the clear competitive advantage of the entropy method
vs. BSVSB and random label querying.
